## 4 Reasons Bezel Beats Prong on Emerald Cut Diamond Earrings

Most diamond earrings come in prong settings by default. Jewelers show them first. Buyers buy them without asking. It is the wrong choice for the emerald cut specifically.

Here is exactly why.

### Reason 1: The Price Gap Is Enormous

At 1ct tw, bezel studs in 14K white gold cost [$3,080](https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry/earrings/bezel-set-emerald-cut-diamond-stud-earrings-in-14k-white-gold-1-ct-tw-h-i-si1-si2-item-251746?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). Prong studs in 14K white gold cost [$5,750](https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry/earrings/emerald-cut-diamond-stud-earrings-in-14k-white-gold-1-ct-tw-h-i-si1-si2-item-251830?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). Same two 0.5ct emerald cut diamonds. $2,670 difference.

That gap exists at every size. It is not a sale. It is the pricing structure.

The bezel setting uses less metal than four separate prong assemblies. That reduces labor and material cost — and those savings pass directly to you. The diamonds inside are graded identically.

### Reason 2: Bezel Protects the Corners

The emerald cut has flat, exposed corners — the four clipped ends of the rectangle. Those corners are the most vulnerable point of the stone. Chips almost always start at corners.

In a ring, the stone sits recessed in a setting. In an earring, it hangs freely. The corners face outward and catch on things — your hair, a scarf, a pillowcase seam.

Bezel sets the stone inside a continuous metal rim. The rim covers the girdle and wraps the corners completely. Nothing touches the stone directly.

### Reason 3: No Prong Shadows on the Table

The emerald cut's most striking feature is its large, flat table — the broad face of the stone you look straight into. Step facets reflect light up through it in long, clean lines.

Four prongs sitting above that table break the light. They cast thin shadow lines across the step facets. The effect is subtle but consistent, and it works against exactly the thing you bought the stone for.

Bezel sits at the girdle, not above the stone. Nothing interrupts the face.

### Reason 4: Bezel Stays Secure

Prong tips bend. It happens with rings, but it happens faster with earrings. Earrings swing with your movement. They catch on hair, pillowcases, coat collars. Over years, prong tips migrate outward and stones loosen.

Bezel is a solid strip of metal bent around the entire girdle. There are no tips to splay. There is nothing to catch. The stone stays exactly where it was set.

