      <td>0.5ct</td>
      <td><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry/earrings/bezel-set-emerald-cut-diamond-stud-earrings-in-14k-white-gold-1-ct-tw-h-i-si1-si2-item-251746?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational">$3,080</a></td>
      <td><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry/earrings/bezel-set-emerald-cut-diamond-stud-earrings-in-14k-yellow-gold-1-ct-tw-h-i-si1-si2-item-251786?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational">$3,080</a></td>
      <td><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry/earrings/bezel-set-emerald-cut-diamond-stud-earrings-in-platinum-1-ct-tw-h-i-si1-si2-item-251747?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational">$3,180</a></td>
      <td><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry/earrings/emerald-cut-diamond-stud-earrings-in-14k-white-gold-1-ct-tw-h-i-si1-si2-item-251830?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational">$5,750</a></td>
      <td><strong>$2,670</strong></td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

The diamonds inside the bezel and prong versions are graded identically: H-I color, SI1-SI2 clarity. You are not getting better stones in the prong version. You are paying more for a different setting style.

> "In earrings, bezel is almost always the right choice for a step-cut stone. The rectangular shape needs a clean frame — and bezel gives you exactly that. You also save thousands compared to the prong version. That money can go toward a heavier carat weight or a second pair entirely." — Farzana Hasan, **[Diamond Critics](https://diamondcritics.com/about-farzana/)**

